    {
      "id": "2c13e7aa094376bd7fc4b22e20714bf9e1e905b7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2014-04-16 18:07:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nHonestly, I don't think using a \"check patch\" script is the _right_ way to do this; the onus should be on the developer and reviewers to ensure console \"integrity\" is maintained.\n\nBut, with that said, this patch looks good to me. My gripe is more due to a philosophical difference, than a knock on the change itself.\n\n+1, Looks good to me.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "51c5fa33d0d9967848213c70ccb678110dcaf62e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2014-04-18 12:47:05.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi Prakash,\n\n> Honestly, I don't think using a \"check patch\" script is the _right_ way to do this; the onus should be on the developer and reviewers to ensure console \"integrity\" is maintained.\n\nThe main idea (due to Peter) is that the HPDD-checkpatch style checker will add these comments on gerrit and thereby encourage reviewers to scrutinize the assertions and error messages being added. We'll see if that has the intended effect.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "82342db605f0799776af8248f073b7595cf54755",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-04-19 08:24:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2\n\n(2 comments)\n\nI agree with John that this should be a second line of defense, and developers should think more before adding these things in the first place. That said, it also makes it easier for inspectors to see when CERROR() or LASSERT() are being added to ensure they are being used appropriately.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
